Individuals' educational access and outcomes are greatly influenced by their family and community. A child's family and community can give them with tools and support that will help them succeed in school, such as access to books and educational materials, encouragement to seek education, and financial assistance for college. A child's family and community, on the other hand, can provide challenges to educational access and achievement, such as poverty, a lack of access to quality schools, and discrimination. Policies and initiatives focusing on parental and community educational engagement can assist address issues of equity, diversity, and inclusion by offering support and resources to families and communities that might not otherwise have access to them. Programs that offer financial aid for college or support and tools to help parents navigate the education system, for example, can help level the playing field for children from low-income homes. Programs aimed at increasing parental and community involvement in education can also contribute to a more inclusive and equitable educational environment. Programs that provide parent education and training on how to support their child's education, for example, can assist empower parents to advocate for their child's education and become more involved in the educational system. Furthermore, community-based programs such as tutoring or mentorship can help to improve educational outcomes for students from low-income neighborhoods by offering additional support and resources that can help reduce the achievement gap. In conclusion, policies and programs focusing on parental and community educational engagement can play an important role in addressing issues of equity, diversity, and inclusion by providing support and resources to families and communities that might not otherwise have access to them, as well as increasing parental and community engagement in education. 